liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The health ministry in the Gaza Strip says an Israeli air strike hit a building in the Al Shifa hospital complex, killing one Palestinian, but Israel has denied it targeted the hospital. Gaza's health ministry spokesman said 170 patients and hundreds of displaced Palestinians were in the hospital building at the time. He said several Palestinians were wounded in the strike. But an Israeli military spokesperson, when asked about the claim, said: "There was no IDF (Israel Defense Forces) strike on the Shifa hospital." Earlier, Al Jazeera TV and Hamas-affiliated Al Aqsa radio said Israeli forces had targeted a solar panel system at the hospital complex. Chief IDF spokesperson Rear Admiral Daniel Hagari, asked about those reports during a briefing with reporters, said: "We didn't attack, to the best of my knowledge, solar panels in the Shifa hospital." Israel's military has previously presented alleged evidence showing some hospitals are used by Hamas as bases of operation but these claims cannot be independently verified. Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel denies hospital strike which Gaza health ministry says killed one

He said several Palestinians were wounded in the strike.
But an Israeli military spokesperson, when asked about the claim, said: "There was no IDF (Israel Defense Forces) strike on the Shifa hospital."

Chief IDF spokesperson Rear Admiral Daniel Hagari, asked about those reports during a briefing with reporters, said: "We didn't attack, to the best of my knowledge, solar panels in the Shifa hospital."
Israel's military has previously presented alleged evidence showing some hospitals are used by Hamas as bases of operation but these claims cannot be independently verified.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Labor MP Bill Shorten has called the federal Greens "opportunists" after they walked out of the Senate in support of Palestinians yesterday. During Senate Question Time, senator Mehreen Faruqi declared the Greens brought the "people's protest" into parliament after leading her colleagues in a walkout. Senator Janet Rice raised a printed page showing the Palestinian flag as they walked out. Mr Shorten this morning said no one thinks this move helps. "I don't think the Greens walking out helps a single soul anywhere. I think that is just political grand standing. I don't know how that helps," he said "I think that the Government has the right line of length. We want to make sure that we are supporting the humanitarian pause. "We want to see relief get through to innocent Palestinian civilians. "But you know, with the Greens … they don't walk out over Hamas. So I think that these guys are opportunists." He said the Australian government's messaging on the issue is right. "This most recent shocking conflict was triggered by Hamas crossing the borders into Israel," he said. "I think the government has made its position clear that Israel has a right to defend itself. "We also want to make sure that, to the extent that it is possible, the rules of war are followed. "That means these civilians, these Palestinian civilians, it's not their fault. It's shameful. What we're seeing is very difficult too." You can read more about what transpired yesterday here:

It was also a meeting 18 months in the making to stabilise the relationship between the two, especially when it comes to trade. Geoff Raby, former Australian ambassador to China, says the Australia-China trade relationship will continue to go from strength to strength, and bilateral relations have returned to "normal". liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market is likely to slip in morning trade, snapping its five-day winning streak. ASX futures were down 0.2%, following a subdued performance on Wall Street overnight. US markets have just finished trading, with the Dow Jones, S & P 500 and Nasdaq Composite rising 0.1%, 0.2% and 0.3% respectively. The main US stock indexes were trading in the red, until they made a final-hour recovery. Last week, the S & P climbed 5.9% and the Nasdaq surged 6.6% (marking their best weeks since November 2022). The Dow jumped 5.1% last week (its biggest weekly gain since October 2022) on hopes the US Federal Reserve is near the end of its rate-hiking cycle.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wall Street extends gains, ASX to open lower

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If there's one lesson our new Reserve Bank governor hasn't gleaned from her predecessor, it is the danger of being overly precise. Michele Bullock has been adamant that taming inflation in a timely matter is a top priority. A fortnight ago, however, she added a dash of precision to the message. The RBA, she said, "would not hesitate" to lift rates again if there was a "material" change to the inflation forecasts. Lo and behold, when the September quarter inflation figures dropped, the numbers were hotter than the RBA's forecasts. That put a question mark over the bank's well-telegraphed plan to gradually bring inflation back to between 2 and 3 per cent by 2025. Many now argue that the material change clause that's been inserted into the dialogue looks to have been triggered and the RBA has little option but to follow through. For more, here's the latest analysis from business editor Ian Verrender :
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why the Reserve Bank will probably lift interest rates on Melbourne Cup Day even though it doesn't need to

featuredLink.title: Candour and credibility: Has Michele Bullock backed herself into a corner?
